The focus is on improving the preprocessing time of existing algorithms, which suggests that the paper is likely to be in the "Data Structures and Algorithms" (cs.DS) category. The problem of constructing distance oracles is closely related to computational geometry, which suggests that the paper may also be in the "Computational Geometry" (cs.CG) category. The paper also involves analyzing the performance of the algorithms in terms of approximation guarantees and running time, which suggests that it may be in the "Discrete Mathematics" (cs.DM) category. The use of techniques such as matrix multiplication and spectral sparsification suggests that the paper may also be in the "Information Theory" (cs.IT) category.
